'''Ogura Shrine''' (おぐらじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Otsu|Q202907|WD=Q202907|1=Ōtsu}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and under the former {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}.

In addition to Ogura Shrine, four other shrines are enshrined here: Ōmiya Shrine, Wakamiya Shrine, Imamiya Shrine, and Shingū Shrine.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, during the transfer of the capital to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōmi-kyō|1=UNKNOWN}} in Emperor {{ill|lt=Tenji|Q314802|WD=Q314802|1=Emperor Tenji}} 6 ({{ill|lt=667|Q30702|WD=Q30702|1=667}}), an ascetic called Kadaifu (also written Gadaifu/Kadaifu) Sennin, who accompanied the move, invited a {{ill|lt=divided spirit|Q195793|WD=Q195793|1=Bunrei}} from {{ill|lt=Niukawakami Shrine|Q246370|WD=Q246370|1=Niukawakami Shrine (Q246370)}} in {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}} to Ogi, marking the foundation. Later, in {{ill|lt=Jōgan|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} 1 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), it is said to have been moved to the present site by {{ill|lt=Minamoto no Tōru|Q1284268|WD=Q1284268|1=Minamoto no Tōru}}. The present site is also said to have been where Ōmiya Shrine was founded a year earlier, in {{ill|lt=Ten'an|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} 2 ({{ill|lt=858|Q30371|WD=Q30371|1=858}}), by Prince {{ill|lt=Koretaka|Q11492950|WD=Q11492950|1=Koretaka-shinnō}}, son of {{ill|lt=Emperor Montoku|Q357225|WD=Q357225|1=Emperor Montoku}}. At the former site, Takitsubo Shrine, now the {{ill|lt=okumiya|Q11445659|WD=Q11445659|1=Okumiya}}, is enshrined ({{Coord|35|06|21.9|N|135|51|13.1|E|scale:25000}}). Later, in {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|WD=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=902|Q23587|WD=Q23587|1=902}}), Wakamiya Shrine was enshrined.

In Engi 8 ({{ill|lt=908|Q30463|WD=Q30463|1=908}}), it was listed as an {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki shikinaisha|1=UNKNOWN}}.

In {{ill|lt=Jōgen|Q1324833|WD=Q1324833|lt=Jōgen|1=Jōgen (Heian period)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=977|Q23795|WD=Q23795|1=977}}), {{ill|lt=Minamoto no Mitsunaka|Q2531241|WD=Q2531241|1=Minamoto no Mitsunaka}} moved to this area and stayed for ten years.

In {{ill|lt=Kenkyū|Q1193933|WD=Q1193933|1=Kenkyū}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1190|Q19736|WD=Q19736|1=1190}}), Imamiya Shrine and Shingū Shrine were enshrined in the precincts. In the medieval period, it was also called '''Gosha Daigongen''' ('''Daimyōjin''') and drew devotion.

In {{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|WD=Q7766|1=1876}} (Meiji 9), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. In {{ill|lt=1908|Q2056|WD=Q2056|1=1908}} (Meiji 41), it was designated a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shinsen-heihaku-ryō kyōshinsha|1=UNKNOWN}}. The shrine name had at some point become '''Tadosho Shrine''', but in {{ill|lt=1945|Q5240|WD=Q5240|1=1945}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 20) it was restored to the current name and promoted to prefectural shrine<ref>{{Cite web|和書|url=http://ogurajinja.org/yuisyo.html |title=Ogura Shrine History |accessdate=2012-12-23}}</ref>.

